166 /**
167 Find the best index to do 'ref' access on for a table.
168
169 The best index chosen using the following priority list
170 1) A clustered primary key with equality predicates on all keyparts is
171 always chosen.
172 2) A non nullable unique index with equality predicates on
173 all keyparts is preferred over a non-unique index,
174 nullable unique index or unique index where there are some
175 keyparts without equality predicates.
176 3) Otherwise, the index with best cost estimate is chosen.
177
178 As a side-effect, bound_keyparts/read_cost/fanout is set for the first
179 Key_use of every considered key.
180
181 @param tab the table to be joined by the function
182 @param remaining_tables set of tables not included in the
183 partial plan yet.
184 @param idx the index in join->position[] where 'tab'
185 is added to the partial plan.
186 @param prefix_rowcount estimate for the number of records returned
187 by the partial plan
188 @param [out] found_condition whether or not there exists a condition
189 that filters away rows for this table.
190 Always true when the function finds a
191 usable 'ref' access, but also if it finds
192 a condition that is not usable by 'ref'
193 access, e.g. is there is an index covering
194 (a,b) and there is a condition only on 'b'.
195 Note that all dependent tables for the
196 condition in question must be in the plan
197 prefix for this to be 'true'. Unmodified

204 @return pointer to Key_use for the index with best 'ref' access, NULL if

1248 /*
1249 Because calculating condition filtering has a cost, it should only
1250 be done if the filter is meaningful. It is meaningful if the query
1251 is an EXPLAIN, or if the filter may influence the QEP.
1252
1253 Note that this means that EXPLAIN FOR CONNECTION will typically
1254 not find a calculated filtering value for the last table in a QEP
1255 (i.e., it will be 1.0).
1256
1257 Calculate condition filter if
1258 1) Condition filtering is enabled, and
1259 2a) Condition filtering is about to be calculated for a scan that
1260 might do join buffering. Rationale: When a table is scanned
1261 and joined with rows in a buffer, constant predicates are
1262 evaluated on rows in the joined table. Only rows that pass the
1263 constant predicates are attempted joined with the prefix rows
1264 in the buffer. The filtering effect is the estimate of how
1265 many rows pass the constant predicate evaluation.

1267 Rationale: filtering only reduces the number of rows sent to
1268 the next step in the join ordering and therefore has no effect

2244 /**
2245 Find a good, possibly optimal, query execution plan (QEP) by a greedy search.
2246
2247 The search procedure uses a hybrid greedy/exhaustive search with controlled
2248 exhaustiveness. The search is performed in N = card(remaining_tables)
2249 steps. Each step evaluates how promising is each of the unoptimized tables,
2250 selects the most promising table, and extends the current partial QEP with
2251 that table. Currently the most 'promising' table is the one with least
2252 expensive extension.\
2253
2254 There are two extreme cases:
2255 -# When (card(remaining_tables) < search_depth), the estimate finds the
2256 best complete continuation of the partial QEP. This continuation can be
2257 used directly as a result of the search.
2258 -# When (search_depth == 1) the 'best_extension_by_limited_search'
2259 considers the extension of the current QEP with each of the remaining
2260 unoptimized tables.
2261
2262 All other cases are in-between these two extremes. Thus the parameter
2263 'search_depth' controls the exhaustiveness of the search. The higher the
2264 value, the longer the optimizaton time and possibly the better the
2265 resulting plan. The lower the value, the fewer alternative plans are
2266 estimated, but the more likely to get a bad QEP.
2267
2268 All intermediate and final results of the procedure are stored in 'join':
2269 - join->positions : modified for every partial QEP that is explored
2270 - join->best_positions: modified for the current best complete QEP
2271 - join->best_read : modified for the current best complete QEP
2272 - join->best_ref : might be partially reordered
2273
2274 The final optimal plan is stored in 'join->best_positions', and its
2275 corresponding cost in 'join->best_read'.
2276
2277 @note
2278 The following pseudocode describes the algorithm of 'greedy_search':
2279
2280 @code
2281 procedure greedy_search
2282 input: remaining_tables
2283 output: pplan;
2284 {
2285 pplan = <>;
2286 do {
2287 (t, a) = best_extension(pplan, remaining_tables);
2288 pplan = concat(pplan, (t, a));
2289 remaining_tables = remaining_tables - t;
2290 } while (remaining_tables != {})
2291 return pplan;
2292 }
2293
2294 @endcode
2295 where 'best_extension' is a placeholder for a procedure that selects the
2296 most "promising" of all tables in 'remaining_tables'.
2297 Currently this estimate is performed by calling
2298 'best_extension_by_limited_search' to evaluate all extensions of the
2299 current QEP of size 'search_depth', thus the complexity of 'greedy_search'
2300 mainly depends on that of 'best_extension_by_limited_search'.
2301
2302 @par
2303 If 'best_extension()' == 'best_extension_by_limited_search()', then the
2304 worst-case complexity of this algorithm is <=
2305 O(N*N^search_depth/search_depth). When serch_depth >= N, then the
2306 complexity of greedy_search is O(N!).
2307 'N' is the number of 'non eq_ref' tables + 'eq_ref groups' which normally
2308 are considerable less than total numbers of tables in the query.
2309
2310 @par
2311 In the future, 'greedy_search' might be extended to support other
2312 implementations of 'best_extension'.

2599 /**
2600 Find a good, possibly optimal, query execution plan (QEP) by a possibly
2601 exhaustive search.
2602
2603 The procedure searches for the optimal ordering of the query tables in set
2604 'remaining_tables' of size N, and the corresponding optimal access paths to
2605 each table. The choice of a table order and an access path for each table
2606 constitutes a query execution plan (QEP) that fully specifies how to
2607 execute the query.
2608
2609 The maximal size of the found plan is controlled by the parameter
2610 'search_depth'. When search_depth == N, the resulting plan is complete and
2611 can be used directly as a QEP. If search_depth < N, the found plan consists
2612 of only some of the query tables. Such "partial" optimal plans are useful
2613 only as input to query optimization procedures, and cannot be used directly
2614 to execute a query.
2615
2616 The algorithm begins with an empty partial plan stored in 'join->positions'
2617 and a set of N tables - 'remaining_tables'. Each step of the algorithm
2618 evaluates the cost of the partial plan extended by all access plans for
2619 each of the relations in 'remaining_tables', expands the current partial
2620 plan with the access plan that results in lowest cost of the expanded
2621 partial plan, and removes the corresponding relation from
2622 'remaining_tables'. The algorithm continues until it either constructs a
2623 complete optimal plan, or constructs an optimal plartial plan with size =
2624 search_depth.
2625
2626 The final optimal plan is stored in 'join->best_positions'. The
2627 corresponding cost of the optimal plan is in 'join->best_read'.
2628
2629 @note
2630 The procedure uses a recursive depth-first search where the depth of the
2631 recursion (and thus the exhaustiveness of the search) is controlled by the
2632 parameter 'search_depth'.
2633
2634 @note
2635 The pseudocode below describes the algorithm of
2636 'best_extension_by_limited_search'. The worst-case complexity of this
2637 algorithm is O(N*N^search_depth/search_depth). When serch_depth >= N, then
2638 the complexity of greedy_search is O(N!).

2641 @c best_extension_by_limited_search() and @c

2960 /**
2961 Heuristic utility used by best_extension_by_limited_search().
2962 Adds EQ_REF-joined tables to the partial plan without
2963 extensive 'greedy' cost calculation.
2964
2965 When a table is joined by an unique key there is a
2966 1::1 relation between the rows being joined. Assuming we
2967 have multiple such 1::1 (star-)joined relations in a
2968 sequence, without other join types in between. Then all of
2969 these 'eq_ref-joins' will be estimated to return the exact
2970 same number of rows and having identical 'cost' (or 'read_time').
2971
2972 This leads to that we can append such a contiguous sequence
2973 of eq_ref-joins to a partial plan in any order without
2974 affecting the total cost of the query plan. Exploring the
2975 different permutations of these eq_refs in the 'greedy'
2976 optimizations will simply be a waste of precious CPU cycles.
2977
2978 Once we have appended a single eq_ref-join to a partial
2979 plan, we may use eq_ref_extension_by_limited_search() to search
2980 'remaining_tables' for more eq_refs which will form a contiguous
2981 set of eq_refs in the QEP.
2982
2983 Effectively, this chain of eq_refs will be handled as a single
2984 entity wrt. the full 'greedy' exploration of the possible
2985 join plans. This will reduce the 'N' in the O(N!) complexity
2986 of the full greedy search.
2987
2988 The algorithm start by already having a eq_ref joined table
2989 in position[idx-1] when called. It then search for more
2990 eq_ref-joinable 'remaining_tables' which are added directly
2991 to the partial QEP without further cost analysis. The algorithm
2992 continues until it either has constructed a complete plan,
2993 constructed a partial plan with size = search_depth, or could not
2994 find more eq_refs to append.
2995
2996 In the later case the algorithm continues into
2997 'best_extension_by_limited_search' which does a 'greedy'
2998 search for the next table to add - Possibly with later
2999 eq_ref_extensions.
3000
3001 The final optimal plan is stored in 'join->best_positions'. The
3002 corresponding cost of the optimal plan is in 'join->best_read'.
3003

3005 @c best_extension_by_limited_search() and @c
3006 eq_ref_extension_by_limited_search() are closely related to each other and
3007 intentionally implemented using the same pattern wherever possible. If a
3008 change/bug fix is done to either of these also consider if it is relevant for
3009 the other.

3245 Given a partial join order (in join->positions[0..idx-1]) and a subset of
3246 tables within that join order (specified in found_ref), find out how many
3247 distinct row combinations of subset tables will be in the result of the
3248 partial join order.
3249
3250 This is used as follows: Suppose we have a table accessed with a ref-based
3251 method. The ref access depends on current rows of tables in found_ref.
3252 We want to count # of different ref accesses. We assume two ref accesses
3253 will be different if at least one of access parameters is different.
3254 Example: consider a query
3255
3256 SELECT * FROM t1, t2, t3 WHERE t1.key=c1 AND t2.key=c2 AND t3.key=t1.field
3257
3258 and a join order:
3259 t1, ref access on t1.key=c1
3260 t2, ref access on t2.key=c2
3261 t3, ref access on t3.key=t1.field
3262
3263 For t1: n_ref_scans = 1, n_distinct_ref_scans = 1
3264 For t2: n_ref_scans = fanout(t1), n_distinct_ref_scans=1
3265 For t3: n_ref_scans = fanout(t1)*fanout(t2)
3266 n_distinct_ref_scans = #fanout(t1)
3267
3268 Here "fanout(tx)" is the number of rows read by the access method
3269 of tx minus rows filtered out by condition filtering
3270 (pos->filter_effect).
3271
3272 The reason for having this function (at least the latest version of it)
3273 is that we need to account for buffering in join execution.
3274
3275 An edge-case example: if we have a non-first table in join accessed via
3276 ref(const) or ref(param) where there is a small number of different
3277 values of param, then the access will likely hit the disk cache and will
3278 not require any disk seeks.
3279
3280 The proper solution would be to assume an LRU disk cache of some size,
3281 calculate probability of cache hits, etc. For now we just count
3282 identical ref accesses as one.
3283
3284 RETURN
3285 Expected number of row combinations
3286 */

3507 /**
3508 Check interleaving with an inner tables of an outer join for
3509 extension table.
3510
3511 Check if table tab can be added to current partial join order, and
3512 if yes, record that it has been added. This recording can be rolled back
3513 with backout_nj_state().
3514
3515 The function assumes that both current partial join order and its
3516 extension with tab are valid wrt table dependencies.
3517
3518 @verbatim
3519 IMPLEMENTATION
3520 LIMITATIONS ON JOIN ORDER
3521 The nested [outer] joins executioner algorithm imposes these
3522 limitations on join order:
3523 1. "Outer tables first" - any "outer" table must be before any
3524 corresponding "inner" table.
3525 2. "No interleaving" - tables inside a nested join must form a
3526 continuous sequence in join order (i.e. the sequence must not be interrupted
3527 by tables that are outside of this nested join).
3528
3529 #1 is checked elsewhere, this function checks #2 provided that #1 has
3530 been already checked.
3531
3532 WHY NEED NON-INTERLEAVING
3533 Consider an example:
3534
3535 select * from t0 join t1 left join (t2 join t3) on cond1
3536
3537 The join order "t1 t2 t0 t3" is invalid:
3538
3539 table t0 is outside of the nested join, so WHERE condition for t0 is
3540 attached directly to t0 (without triggers, and it may be used to access
3541 t0). Applying WHERE(t0) to (t2,t0,t3) record is invalid as we may miss
3542 combinations of (t1, t2, t3) that satisfy condition cond1, and produce
3543 a null-complemented (t1, t2.NULLs, t3.NULLs) row, which should not have been
3544 produced.
3545
3546 If table t0 is not between t2 and t3, the problem doesn't exist:
3547 If t0 is located after (t2,t3), WHERE(t0) is applied after nested join
3548 processing has finished.
3549 If t0 is located before (t2,t3), predicates like WHERE_cond(t0, t2)
3550 are wrapped into condition triggers, which takes care of correct nested join
3551 processing.
3552
3553 HOW IT IS IMPLEMENTED
3554 The limitations on join order can be rephrased as follows: for valid
3555 join order one must be able to:
3556 1. write down the used tables in the join order on one line.
3557 2. for each nested join, put one '(' and one ')' on the said line
3558 3. write "LEFT JOIN" and "ON (...)" where appropriate
3559 4. get a query equivalent to the query we're trying to execute.
3560
3561 Calls to check_interleaving_with_nj() are equivalent to writing the
3562 above described line from left to right.
3563 A single check_interleaving_with_nj(A,B) call is equivalent to writing
3564 table B and appropriate brackets on condition that table A and
3565 appropriate brackets is the last what was written. Graphically the
3566 transition is as follows:
3567
3568 +---- current position
3569 |
3570 ... last_tab ))) | ( tab ) )..) | ...
3571 X Y Z |
3572 +- need to move to this
3573 position.
3574
3575 Notes about the position:
3576 The caller guarantees that there is no more then one X-bracket by
3577 checking "!(remaining_tables & s->dependent)" before calling this
3578 function. X-bracket may have a pair in Y-bracket.
3579
3580 When "writing" we store/update this auxiliary info about the current
3581 position:
3582 1. cur_embedding_map - bitmap of pairs of brackets (aka nested
3583 joins) we've opened but didn't close.
3584 2. {each NESTED_JOIN structure not simplified away}->counter - number
3585 of this nested join's children that have already been added to to
3586 the partial join order.
3587 @endverbatim
3588
3589 @param tab Table we're going to extend the current partial join with
3590
3591 @retval

3593 order (see NOTE section) updated.
3594 @retval
3595 true Requested join order extension not allowed.
3596 */

4608 /**
4609 Nested joins perspective: Remove the last table from the join order.
4610
4611 @details
4612 Remove the last table from the partial join order and update the nested
4613 joins counters and cur_embedding_map. It is ok to call this
4614 function for the first table in join order (for which
4615 check_interleaving_with_nj has not been called)
4616
4617 This function rolls back changes done by:
4618 - check_interleaving_with_nj(): removes the last table from the partial join
4619 order and update the nested joins counters and cur_embedding_map. It
4620 is ok to call this for the first table in join order (for which
4621 check_interleaving_with_nj() has not been called).
4622
4623 The algorithm is the reciprocal of check_interleaving_with_nj(), hence
4624 parent join nest nodes are updated only when the last table in its child
4625 node is removed. The ASCII graphic below will clarify.
4626
4627 %A table nesting such as <tt> t1 x [ ( t2 x t3 ) x ( t4 x t5 ) ] </tt>is
4628 represented by the below join nest tree.
4629
4630 @verbatim
4631 NJ1
4632 _/ / \
4633 _/ / NJ2
4634 _/ / / \
4635 / / / \
4636 t1 x [ (t2 x t3) x (t4 x t5) ]
4637 @endverbatim
4638
4639 At the point in time when check_interleaving_with_nj() adds the table t5 to
4640 the query execution plan, QEP, it also directs the node named NJ2 to mark
4641 the table as covered. NJ2 does so by incrementing its @c counter
4642 member. Since all of NJ2's tables are now covered by the QEP, the algorithm
4643 proceeds up the tree to NJ1, incrementing its counter as well. All join
4644 nests are now completely covered by the QEP.
4645
4646 backout_nj_state() does the above in reverse. As seen above, the node
4647 NJ1 contains the nodes t2, t3, and NJ2. Its counter being equal to 3 means
4648 that the plan covers t2, t3, and NJ2, @e and that the sub-plan (t4 x t5)
4649 completely covers NJ2. The removal of t5 from the partial plan will first
4650 decrement NJ2's counter to 1. It will then detect that NJ2 went from being
4651 completely to partially covered, and hence the algorithm must continue
4652 upwards to NJ1 and decrement its counter to 2. A subsequent removal of t4
4653 will however not influence NJ1 since it did not un-cover the last table in
4654 NJ2.
4655
4656 @param remaining_tables remaining tables to optimize, must contain 'tab'
4657 @param tab join table to remove, assumed to be the last in
4658 current partial join order.
4659 */
